Scott: And you say, "Okay, CloudFront, you see that machine, that S3 bucket over

628
00:36:16,515 --> 00:36:16,737
Scott: there.".

629
00:36:16,899 --> 00:36:19,039
Scott: Well, yeah, serve that, okay?

630
00:36:19,462 --> 00:36:30,290
Scott: So what this does is, out in front of the--people, you tell--instead of having people visit your S3 bucket and getting the files from the bucket, you use the DNS entry for the CloudFront.

631
00:36:30,671 --> 00:36:36,130
Scott: So people visit the CloudFront, and what happens is they're actually going to end up at a local server.

632
00:36:36,594 --> 00:36:43,303
Scott: It will take the files from your bucket and send them to servers all around the world, right, where people can get them from.

633
00:36:43,323 --> 00:36:51,770
Scott: So that way, if someone reads your webcomic in France, they actually download the JPEG from a French server, and if they're in California, they download the JPEG from a Californian server.

634
00:36:52,233 --> 00:36:53,870
Scott: And they keep adding new edge locations.

635
00:36:54,050 --> 00:36:57,830
Scott: They just added a new edge location in, like, Tokyo or the South--you know, Southeast Asia.

636
00:36:58,632 --> 00:37:14,555
Scott: So if you want to, you know, host videos online or stream videos online, you can use the streaming CloudFront, and now people can stream your videos from a server near them to watch it more quickly instead of having the whole world stream videos from one place, you know, one server.

637
00:37:14,576 --> 00:37:16,454
Scott: This costs a lot of money.

638
00:37:16,474 --> 00:37:19,041
Scott: The more bandwidth you use, it costs even more money.

639
00:37:19,243 --> 00:37:24,030
Scott: But if you actually need that feature, which a lot of people do, it's so easy.

640
00:37:24,192 --> 00:37:25,203
Scott: It's like three clicks.

641
00:37:25,466 --> 00:37:25,850
Scott: It's great.

642
00:37:26,891 --> 00:37:29,061
Scott: The thing is, CloudFront is even better than that.

643
00:37:29,343 --> 00:37:32,818
Scott: You can actually use CloudFront without an S3 bucket.

644
00:37:33,000 --> 00:37:36,110
Scott: You can just have it point at any old DNS entry anywhere.

645
00:37:36,795 --> 00:37:39,444
Scott: So you can have CloudFront point at some machine.

646
00:37:39,485 --> 00:37:43,510
Scott: you've got set even on Linode, but usually you're going to point it at an Amazon machine.

647
00:37:44,295 --> 00:37:52,075
Scott: And you can have an application that serves up dynamic shit, as long as it always serves the same thing at the same URL, right?

648
00:37:52,459 --> 00:37:54,642
Scott: And then CloudFront will serve that out front.

649
00:37:54,783 --> 00:37:57,955
Scott: So, for example, you know, I was talking about thumbnails before.

650
00:37:58,419 --> 00:38:10,619
Scott: You could write a thing that will thumbnail images and serve them out, and then people hit the CloudFront, the CloudFront hits your server, the server generates the thumbnail, sends the thumbnail to the CloudFront.

651
00:38:10,680 --> 00:38:26,379
Scott: Now that thumbnail is in 20 places in the world where anyone can get it easily without even hitting your server, and in case that expires out in the world, you know, the cache expires and people need to hit your server again, you've stored the thumbnail in S3 where you can get it again without having to generate it again.

652
00:38:26,399 --> 00:38:30,641
Scott: So you can make like the ultimate thumbnail generator amongst other things.

653
00:38:30,662 --> 00:38:38,016
Scott: You could have all sorts of crazy ideas of ways to generate stuff, but the thing is you can't use query parameters in the URL.

654
00:38:38,056 --> 00:38:39,509
Scott: It has to be the URL itself.

655
00:38:40,031 --> 00:38:45,566
Scott: So you need to have some sort of code like slash with slash 100 slash, you know, something like that.

656
00:38:45,607 --> 00:38:47,769
Scott: You can't do question mark with equals.

657
00:38:47,809 --> 00:38:48,407
Scott: That will not work.

658
00:38:50,013 --> 00:38:57,349
Scott: But yeah, I mean, I'm not going to go through all the Amazon web services just because there's so many of them, but they've got a lot.

659
00:38:57,770 --> 00:38:59,810
Rym: They're surprisingly easy to use, too.

660
00:39:00,510 --> 00:39:01,362
Scott: Well, here's the thing.

