682
00:40:18,039 --> 00:40:21,907
Scott: There's all kinds of stuff like that going on about there.

683
00:40:23,330 --> 00:40:23,670
Scott: I don't know.

684
00:40:25,597 --> 00:40:31,010
Scott: The other problem with it, and this is actually I think my biggest problem with it, is take Linode, our hosting for the web.

685
00:40:32,315 --> 00:40:36,462
Scott: If there's a problem with the hardware, our Linode is a virtual machine.

686
00:40:36,543 --> 00:40:37,675
Scott: It's not a real computer.

687
00:40:38,219 --> 00:40:41,557
Scott: It's on a real computer, but it's not the computer.

688
00:40:41,638 --> 00:40:42,449
Scott: It's a virtual machine.

689
00:40:42,790 --> 00:40:46,403
Rym: Which is kind of the way all hosting and servers are going.

690
00:40:46,524 --> 00:40:48,570
Scott: Unless you pay for dedicated hosting, which is dumb.

691
00:40:48,570 --> 00:40:52,017
Rym: No, but even then, that's the end run right now.

692
00:40:52,038 --> 00:40:53,289
Rym: That's the next big horizon.

693
00:40:54,193 --> 00:41:01,594
Scott: Because it's most economical is to have a few big machines, and then to use the entire machine, you need to split it up into smaller machines.

694
00:41:01,615 --> 00:41:06,341
Rym: And also, unlike the old early days of virtualization, I mean with hypervisors and Linux kernels.

695
00:41:06,623 --> 00:41:10,142
Scott: And the stuff they have in the CPUs now, like vPro and VTX.

696
00:41:10,223 --> 00:41:19,110
Rym: Yep, so basically running a virtual machine is not like the old days, where you're basically emulating an entire hardware stack for this computer to think it's real.

697
00:41:19,650 --> 00:41:24,430
Rym: The computer knows it's fake, and acts accordingly related to the hardware.

698
00:41:26,965 --> 00:41:32,038
Scott: So if something happens, to say the hardware that our line node happens to be on, they just move it to another one.

699
00:41:32,138 --> 00:41:33,410
Scott: We don't even know that there's a problem.

700
00:41:33,950 --> 00:41:34,398
Scott: Right?

701
00:41:34,439 --> 00:41:43,756
